Comments: Genome sequencing as part of The One Thousand Microbial Genomes Phase 4 (KMG IV) project

Isolation Comments: isolated from Durban region of South Africa, degrades 1,2-dichloroethane (1,2-DCA)
Comments: Ancylobacter aquaticus sp. strain UV5, isolated from Durban region of South Africa, degrades 1,2-dichloroethane (1,2-DCA). Here we report the draft genome sequence of A. aquaticus UV5. This study not only will allow insights in to 1,2-DCA degradation aspect of the strain but also to predict genes responsible to degrade other xenobiotic compounds.

Taxon Lineage Names: cellular organisms;Bacteria;Pseudomonadota;Gammaproteobacteria;Pseudomonadales;Pseudomonadaceae;Pseudomonas;Pseudomonas aeruginosa group;Pseudomonas aeruginosa;Pseudomonas aeruginosa AES-1R
Isolation Source: the sputum of a 14 month old infant with cystic fibrosis
Isolation Comments: isolated from the sputum of a 14 month old infant with cystic fibrosis
Comments: Pseudomonas aeruginosa AES-1R was isolated from the sputum of a 14 month old infant with cystic fibrosis.P. aeruginosa strains have adapted to growth in the cystic fibrosis lung through gene deletions, acquisitions and mutations that set these strains apart genomically from environmental strains. Furthermore, while most CF strains are genotypically different from person to person, some clones are found in a large proportion of CF patients, indicating they are probably transmissible and are often more virulent. Such clones include the Australian Epidemic Strain-1 (AES-1) which infects 10-40% of patients attending CF clinics in eastern Australia. AES-1R is an acute infection isolate of AES-1 and as such its genome represents the initial infective phase of AES-1 which will likely yield vital information on the genetic characteristics of this epidemic strain.

Taxon Lineage Names: cellular organisms;Bacteria;Terrabacteria group;Bacillota;Bacilli;Lactobacillales;Streptococcaceae;Streptococcus;Streptococcus phocae;Streptococcus phocae subsp. salmonis
Assembly Method: Newbler v. 2.7; CLC Genomics Workbench v.
Comments: Streptococcus phocae is a Gram-positive fish pathogen that has an important impact on the Chilean salmon industry. Here, we report the genome sequence of S. phocae strain C-4 isolated from Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar). The genome sequence of S. phocae revealed a number of interesting features and genes related to its possible virulence factors, including genes assocciated to colonization, biofilm formation, invasion, and destruction of the host tissues such as hemolysins, collagen adhesion protein and capsule biosynthesis proteins.
